Found it. In `exp2reg`, when the expression is a local variable with pending jumps (i.e. `!i` where `i` is a local), the function passes the local's register as the destination of the boolean materialization, clobbering the local.

ROOT CAUSE: `src/be_code.c:455-472` (`exp2reg`). When `e` is `ETLOCAL` (e.g. the operand `i` in `!i`), `var2reg` returns the local's register (line 443) without changing `e->type` to `ETREG`. The branch `if (hasjump(e))` then sets `reg = e->v.idx` (line 462) and emits `code_bool(finfo, reg, …)` at lines 464–465. Because `reg` is the local variable's slot, the `LDBOOL` instructions overwrite the local. So in `def f(i) var j = !i; return i end`, after evaluating `!i` the parameter `i` has been replaced by the boolean result, and `f(1)` returns `false`.

LOCAL FIX: In `exp2reg`, if `hasjump(e)` and the source isn't a fresh temporary (i.e. `e->type` is `ETLOCAL`/`ETCONST`, or equivalently `reg < finfo->freereg` and it's not an `ETREG`), allocate a new destination register and use it instead of the local's slot. Concretely, before line 462:
```c
if (e->type != ETREG) {
    reg = (dst >= 0 && dst < finfo->freereg) ? dst : be_code_allocregs(finfo, 1);
} else {
    reg = e->v.idx;
}
```
and use that `reg` for the subsequent `code_bool` calls. This ensures the boolean materialization writes to a temp, never to a named local.

GLOBAL FIX: The bug class is "code generator treats `ETLOCAL`/`ETCONST` operand registers as writable scratch." Enforce a single invariant throughout `be_code.c`: a destination register must always be `ETREG` (a freshly owned temp at/above `finfo->freereg`). Centralize this with a helper like `exp2anyreg_writable(e)` that, for any non-`ETREG` expression, materializes the value into a newly allocated register and sets `e->type = ETREG` before any opcode that mutates the register is emitted. Audit `unaryexp`, `binaryexp`, `exp2reg`'s jump-materialization path, and `code_suffix` to use it. Add an assertion in `codeABC`/`codeABx` that any register written as the `A` operand is either `>= finfo->freereg-allocated` or explicitly the assignment target — catching this whole family of "stomped a local" bugs at compile time of the bytecode.
